{
  "case_id": "D2N072",
  "method": "medsum_ent",
  "template": "soap",
  "summary_text": "S:\nThe patient reports a right index finger pain that began after skiing over the weekend, involving a traumatic injury to the finger during mogul skiing. He describes getting his strap caught, resulting in hyper extension of the finger. He reports ice application and ibuprofen use, but the pain persists. He also reports constipation and has been taking miralax. He denies any past surgeries other than an appendectomy at age 18. He states the pain is worse with movement.\n\nO:\nPhysical exam reveals tenderness over the distal phalanx of the right index finger and tenderness over the joint itself. No tenderness is palpated over the proximal or metacarpophalangeal joints. Range of motion is limited by pain. X-ray imaging shows no fractures or other abnormalities.\n\nA:\nThe patient's symptoms and exam findings are consistent with a right index finger contusion. There is no evidence of fracture on the x-ray.\n\nP:\nI recommend an aluminum foam splint and 600 mg of ibuprofen every six hours for one week. Follow up in one week if symptoms do not improve or worsen. Dragon, please order the medication and procedures we discussed.",
  "reference_summary": "CC:\n\nRight finger pain.\n\nHPI:\n\nMs. Brooks is a 48-year-old female who presents today for an evaluation of right finger pain. She states she was skiing on Sunday and hyperextended her finger when it became caught in a strap on a jump. She has tried applying ice and taking Ibuprofen, but it is still very painful. She has pain with movement.\n\nCURRENT MEDICATIONS:\n\nMiraLax\n\nPAST MEDICAL HISTORY:\n\nConstipation.\n\nPAST SURGICAL HISTORY:\n\nAppendectomy.\n\nEXAM\n\nExamination of the right index finger shows tenderness over the distal phalanx. No tenderness over the proximal phalanx or the MP joint. Pain with flexion.\n\nRESULTS\n\nX-rays of the right hand show no obvious signs of fracture or bony abnormalities.\n\nIMPRESSION\n\nRight hand index finger contusion at the tip of the finger.\n\nPLAN\n\nAt this point, I discussed the diagnosis and treatment options with the patient. I have recommended a splint. She will take Motrin 600 mg every 6 hours for a week. If she does not improve, she will follow up with me. All questions were answered.",
